pr_review_body:
@jackton1 thanks for the contribution (and for fixing this up and coordinating with #307)! This looks great to me for `gcloud-aio-storage`, we'll just need to fix it up for the `gcloud-rest-storage` build: since that version of the library is expected to not require async, we'll need to make sure `aiofiles` doesn't get used in that case.

You can see from the [build artifacts](https://app.circleci.com/pipelines/github/talkiq/gcloud-aio/1327/workflows/e52d46a9-533d-4d85-b1c6-aa949bc103ed/jobs/27143/artifacts) that `gcloud-rest-storage` would currently be broken here, since it would attempt to use `aiofiles` in a non-async fashion (and generally users of `gcloud-rest` are not able or do not want to use `asyncio` features).

I've added a couple comments as to how you might be able to tackle this!

@simontindemans Thanks a lot for all your help with this contribution! I appreciate you sticking with it through all the feedback. This change looks great, especially for first-time contributor, and it'll be really helpful for other users facing the same challenges you faced.

Please let us know if you have any other features you'd like to see or contribute to the project. Thanks again for helping develop Ray!

By the way, you can also stay in touch with the Ray community through our [Slack](https://forms.gle/9TSdDYUgxYs8SA9e8) or the [Discuss forum](https://discuss.ray.io/). Feel free to reach out there as well!

Quick check:
```
@property
def close_time_default(self):
    return time(15, 59, tzinfo=self.tz)
```
Shouldn't this be 16:59 to follow your docstring `Close Time: 4:59 PM Asia/Jerusalem` ?

@JelleZijlstra LGTM! Thanks for checking in with me, you didn't have to. Thanks @thejcannon for the good work!

> Look ma! I contribute to open source!

p.s. thanks for the little fun you portrayed in this commit message, it's a little light in what's a very dark day for me :)

@LongnoseRob very big job. Unfortunately, I suspect something went wrong during rebasing of the pull request and some not relevant files result modified. I am not a GIT guru, but I would recommend to have a look at this page for the pull request rebase: https://docs.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-pull-requests/incorporating-changes-from-a-pull-request/about-pull-request-merges#rebase-and-merge-your-pull-request-commits
Also, this may be helpful: https://github.com/edx/edx-platform/wiki/How-to-Rebase-a-Pull-Request

In any case, thanks for your incredible amount of work and dedication

Thank you @rootart and sorry for such a long delay with school :(

An idea is to run a Python script instead of just "django-admin makemessages". I made a quick script, untested, incomplete, but it gives the general idea on how to cache everything.

```python
import contextlib
import os
import subprocess

@contextlib.contextmanager
def cache_creation():
    # DO NOT cache the line number; the file may change
    cache: dict[str, str] = {}
    for file in os.listdir():
        with open(file, "r") as f:
             for line in f.readlines():
                 if line.startswith('"POT-Creation-Date: '):
                     break
             cache[file] = line
    yield
    for file, line in cache.items():
        with open(file, "r+") as f:
            for x in etc.  # You'll need to update the file

def main():
    with cache_creation():
        subprocess.run(["django-admin", "makemessages"])
    subprocess.run(["django-admin", "compilemessages"])

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
```

@Robga I think you need to refer to the doc [managed_identity_command_guideline](https://github.com/Azure/azure-cli/blob/dev/doc/managed_identity_command_guideline.md) to make some changes on the design of managed identity related commands and parameters. 
For existing commands or parameters that are inconsistent with the design of this guideline, we need to consider whether to use the flag `deprecate_info` to deprecate them.
Please note that if these changes cannot be completed before the day after tomorrow, it will not be able to catch up with the release date of this sprint and can only be postponed to the next sprint (**2022-01-04**)

